photo.title: Woodcut device of Denys Roce
photo.description: Woodcut device (94 x 69 mm.) of Denys Roce, depicting his arms on a shield, supported by two griffins, hanging from a rose tree with a dog lying at its foot and Roce's monogram "DR" in the background, the whole surrounded by the words ALAVENTVRE TOVT VIENT APONIT QVI PEVT ATENDRE DENIS ROCE (the S in Denis reversed). "[T]hird of Roce's four devices ... The coat of arms may be the legitimate arms of the printer, who had come to France from Scotland. The dogs in the device denote alertness and the scallop shell is the emblem of pilgrims to the shrine of St. James of Campostella [sic]. The rose tree is, of course, a pun on Roce's name."--M. Harman, Printer's and publisher's devices in incunabula in the University of Illinois Library, no. 31. Printed in an incunable edition of St. Augustine's De virtute psalmorum (Paris : Etienne Jehannot for Denis Roce, between 26 June 1500 and 29 May 1501; ISTC ia01352000). Established heading: Roce, Denys, active 1490-1517 Penn Libraries call number: Inc A-1352 All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.title: Ownership inscription of Heinrich Fuchs (1624-1689)
photo.description: Henrici Vulpij Vicarij Generalis [Mid-17th-century ms. ownership inscription of Heinrich Fuchs (1624-1689), canon of the Kathedrale St. Nikolaus in Fribourg, Switzerland, and vicar general of the diocese of Lausanne (1658-1663), who inherited a substantial portion of Peter Falck's library. According to this description of another of Falck's books with similar provenance, "After his death Falck's library passed to his daughter Ursula von Praroman. It was subsequently divided between her two sons Nikolaus and Wilhelm, and passed down through their families, to be more or less reunited in the late 17th century in the Capuchin convent at Fribourg. The present volume was one of those inherited by Wilhelm; this group passed by descent to one Anna Marie von Lanthen-Heidt, a wealthy noblewoman who had married Wilhelm's grandson Nikolaus von Praroman en secondes noces. After her husband's death in 1675 Anna gave the books to her friend the vicar-general Heinrich Fuchs. Fuchs in turn gave part of the books to the Capuchins the year before he died; the remainder passed to the convent after his death in 1689." (For more information on Falck's library, see A. Wagner, Peter Falcks Bibliothek und humanistische Bildung (Bern: P. Haupt, 1926).) VIAF entry: Fuchs, Heinrich, 1624-1689] Penn Libraries call number: Inc A-1192 All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.title: Ownership inscription of Peter Falck (ca. 1468-1519)
photo.description: Petri Falck & Amicorum Non solum Iherosolimis fuisse Sed Iherolsolimis Bene Vixisse Laudandum est. Peter Falck 1516 [Early ms. ownership inscription of humanist Peter Falck (ca. 1468-1519) and friends in red ink, struck through in brown ink, followed by early ms. inscription quoting a pious saying of St. Jerome in red ink in the same hand between drawings of a Jerusalem cross and an unidentified symbol. Beneath these in dark ink is Falck's dated 16th-century autograph, the name struck through, above a (later?) drawing of his coat of arms. Peter Falck was a Swiss humanist known to Erasmus (cf. his entry in Contemporaries of Erasmus) who made pilgrimages to Jerusalem in 1515 and 1519. He contracted plague during the second pilgrimage and died at Rhodes. The pious inscription in red ink is probably to be associated with his first pilgrimage. Established heading: Falck, Peter, approximately 1468-1519] Penn Libraries call number: Inc A-1192 All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.title: Bookplate of Emil Starkenstein (1884-1942)
photo.description: EX LIBRIS STARKENSTEIN [Bookplate of Emil Starkenstein (1884-1942), clinical pharmacology pioneer. A professor at the Univerzita Karlova in Prague, he fled to Holland when the Nazis invaded Czechoslovakia in 1938. In 1941 he was sent to Mauthausen where he perished, though his wife and daughter went into hiding and survived. After the war his scientific papers were donated to Czechoslovakia and are now housed at the Univerzita Karlova. Starkenstein's library was sold before his death to book dealer Ludwig Gottschalk, who hid it from the Nazis and sold it off piecemeal after emigrating to the United States following World War II. Established heading: Starkenstein, Emil, 1884-1942] Penn Libraries call number: Inc V-259 Folio All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.title: Armorial bookplate of James Wyllie Guild (1826-1894)
photo.description: Bookplate (with motto: Fortis in arduis) of James Wyllie Guild (1826-1894), Scottish public accountant and antiquarian. The son of a solicitor, he was born in Arbroath, Scotland, and educated at the Royal High School in Edinburgh. A founding member of the Institute of Accountants and Actuaries in Glasgow (IAAG), he served as its secretary (1867-1873), president (1873-1881), and treasurer (1881-1894). In 1851 he married Clarissa Finlay, with whom he had ten children. Over 3000 items from his library and antiquarian collections were sold at auction in April 1888; cf. Catalogue of the Valuable Library of J. Wyllie Guild ... (Edinburgh: Chapman, 1888). For his biography, see his entry in T.A. Lee, Seekers of Truth: The Scottish Founders of Modern Public Accountancy (Oxford: JAI Press, 2006). Established heading: Guild, James Wyllie Penn Libraries call number: Inc T-372 Folio All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.title: Bookplate of George Dunn (1864-1912), English bibliographer and book collector
photo.description: Bookplate of George Dunn (1864-1912), English bibliographer and book collector. From his obituary: On Tuesday of last week there died suddenly from pneumonia, at the age of forty-seven, a man whose remarkable gifts and attainments deserve more than the few paragraphs of record that have appeared in the public press. Mr. George Dunn, of Woolley Hall, near Maidenhead, was a member of a well-known Northumbrian Catholic family. He was educated at Beaumont College, Windsor, and at Stonyhurst, and was afterwards called to the Bar, though he never practised as a barrister. Inheriting from his father, the late George Dunn, of Bath House, Newcastle, large estates both in Northumberland and Berkshire, together with sufficient revenues, he was able to indulge the tastes of a scholar and collector of early printed books, mediaeval bindings, manuscripts, old silver, and old clocks, as well as those of a sportsman and keen angler, an astronomer and a student of forestry. Of none of these things was he content to have a superficial knowledge. Indeed, it may be said that he handled nothing without mastering it completely ... With these and other interests and pursuits George Dunn lived a tranquil and sequestered life, unmarried and alone in a large house, where he occasionally entertained one or other of the small band of intimates to whom he was devoted and by whom he was beloved. Neatly dressed, shy, spare, and rather below the middle height, he might sometimes be seen entering the British Museum or the Bodleian Library, or quietly turning over the book-treasures in the London sale rooms. But he never attended meetings or went into society, or gave the smallest encouragement to mere acquaintances. He was a Conservative in politics, a model landlord, and a loyal son of the Catholic Church. -- "Mr. George Dunn," The Times (11 March 1912), p. 11, issue 39843, col C. Established heading: Dunn, George, 1864-1912 Penn Libraries call numbers: Inc S-532 Folio All images from this book Inc S-820 Folio All images from this book

photo.title: Autograph of Pierre Cousturier (1475?-1537)
photo.description: petrus sutoris septem Ingenuarum artium magister Iuris su[m]mi ponti ficis bac[caulaureus] [Autograph of Petrus Sutoris. According to the bookseller's description of this work, he is to be identified with "the Sorbonne theologian and Carthusian monk, Petrus Sutor (Pierre Cousturier, ca. 1475-1537), who was involved in bitter controversies with Erasmus" (E.K Schreiber, catalogue 20, no. 5). If that is so, this inscription should be dated prior to 1510, when Cousturier received his doctorate in theology (he entered the Carthusian order in 1511). It might possibly date to the period when he was teaching at the Collège de Sainte-Barbe, ca. 1495-ca. 1502 (the work in which it appears is dated ca. 1498-1500). Cf. P.G. Bietenholz and T.B. Deutscher, eds., Contemporaries of Erasmus v. 1 (Toronto: U of Toronto Press, 1985), p. 352. According to Bietenholz and Deutscher, Cousturier "oppose[d] the reformist goals and methods advocated by the humanists, whom Cousturier saw as radical and even heretical reformers" (ibid.). Established heading: Cousturier, Pierre 1475?-1537] Penn Libraries call number: Inc S-444 Folio All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.title: Ownership inscription of the court library of the Fürstpropstei Ellwangen
photo.description: Ex Bibliotheca aulica R[everen]d[issi]mi & Ill[ustrissi]mi Principis Elvacensis Ownership inscription of the court library of the Fürstpropstei Ellwangen (or, Bibliotheca Elvacensis, Ellwanger Hofbibliothek, Bibliotheca Aulica Elvacensis). This was the court library of the Fürstpropstei Ellwangen (English article here). Originally founded as a Benedictine monastery in the eighth century and raised to the eminence of a Reichsabtei in the ninth, the original Stift Ellwangen had by the early 15th century declined to the point that the Benedictines abandoned it. In 1460 the foundation was given over to a college of secular (Augustinian) canons presided over by a Fürstpropst (prince-provost), who ruled not only the college itself but a small principality centered on the city of Ellwangen (near the eastern border of what is now Baden-Württemberg). The library was a later development, its volumes acquired during the 17th and 18th centuries as the prince-provost's private collection. The college was secularized in 1802; the library was dissolved in 1806, most of the books remaining in Ellwangen to form the basis of the collection of the short-lived Katholisch-Theologische Friedrichs-Universität Ellwangen (1812-1817), subsequently absorbed into the Universität Tübingen as its theological faculty (cf. H. Hummel, ed., Katalog der Inkunabeln in Bibliotheken der Diözese Rottenburg-Stuttgart (Wiesbaden: Harrassowitz, 1993), p. 290). DNB heading: Stift Ellwangen Penn Libraries call number: Inc P-486 Folio All images from this book
